					   <td>

			
			
			



<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Absor follows up on more necro stuff</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=324529" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/044299-5.html">The death of Necros</a></B><P>

Demrack wrote: "Ok, so if this is to be our only role in large raids where is the necro mana version of the cleric complete heal?"<P>

<B>Not at all. There are other things that a necromancer can do. You all eschew the use of pets on raids, but they work just fine against any creature that doesn't use fear. And there is Dead Man Floating, summoning corpses…<P>

I'm not going to pretend to know everything about how a necromancer works. My concern here is that some of you are calling necromancers useless in any big raid, when it's not true. You may not be able to do a ton of damage to the boss monster, but that is by no means all there is to doing a raid. If you see massive damage dealing as the only way that your necromancer is useful, then that is where we disagree.</B><P>

Musicicus said: "First off clerics are used in Raids more favorably because not only can they heal, but if the raid goes bad, they can return the exp of the bad raid."<P>

<B>And a necromancer can return the corpses so that the cleric can work… No, necromancers have as much to do post and pre raid as any other class, and more than some. And I don't hear most of you concerned with that. The major concern here seems to be that at the 'big' fight you are relegated to a support role, and you don't like that (and that you're not exceedingly efficient at it). In other parts of a raid, clearing or recovering, a necromancer is as useful as any other class (yes, even clerics). I hear that druids are in a similar position. On a raid all they do is a bit of healing and other support stuff…<P>

Oh, and you mentioned DoTs making corpses poof.<P>

They don't. As far as we can tell, it hasn't happened in months. We haven't been able to make it happen. At least not on anything like a raid-level mob. If anyone has seen a high level NPC corpse poof from a DoT in the last three months, please let me know and tell me exactly how and where and when and what. High level mobs shouldn't poof anymore. We've coded it so that it just shouldn't happen. It will happen on rare occasions for lower level stuff, and that's probably not going to change (though we are looking at this whole thing again right now). But the high-level-raid-boss-monster-type-NPC corpses shouldn't poof at all due to a fix we made months ago. Don't let that stop you from using DoTs.</B><P>

LordZemus said: "But let's face it. Yes there is a drawback to our soloing power, and you can't complain of it. First off, having a necromancer or two on a raid is a good safety net. Do you know anyone else who can fd and res? And yes, your guildmates will be willing to let you sacrifice some secondaries once they notice you're the only one left at wipeouts. Cleric or wizard used too much mana? Pump them. Enchanter getting pummeled by a mob? ST, turn your pet's taunt back on (you do leave it off for raids, don't you?) and send it, or cast anything out of the Heart Flutter line, guaranteed to make the mob want to eat you. Throw a shadowbound out to save that tank, because Bond of Death and Deflux WILL hit every mob except the last one, despite these asinine complaints. Oh, and your DoTs do hit. Try using the right ones."<P>

<B>Some folks don't agree with the idea that a class that is exceptionally powerful at all other portions of the game might have to take a power-hit in this one part of the game. And it's not such a big hit, as there are still several useful things that make a necromancer useful on a raid. Thanks for pointing some of them out.</B><P>

GeistTallon wrote:<P>

"LordZemus:<P>

I'm suspicious of you even being a necro. Half the stuff you said doesn't work at all, or isn't a viable option 90% of the time."<P>

<B>I'd love to read your counter arguments to those points of his that you don't agree with.</B><P>

Aerik N'Krosis wrote: "I wish they'd make out pets immune to fear at least (like a mindless undead should be!). Maybe use the owner's resistances for the pet? Or else lower the ubermob resistances now that they can have more than 32k HPs. This way we necros could at least DoT them and make a contribution to the fight that is in keeping with the original PURPOSE of the necromancer."<P>

<B>It seems pretty unlikely that things that are currently immune to spells will be made less immune. But I kinda like the idea of making powerful undead pets immune to fear… In any case, rest assured that I'm passing this thread to the team to read, so it's not like I'm final arbiter on anything you all suggest.</B><P>

Mongo wrote: "1. Ignite/Chill Bones: There is no functional purpose for the skeleton effect. The coolness factor fades very quickly, and the effect has the potential for making an epic encounter harder. <P>

Solution - remove the illusion. These spells do land on some epic encounters, but they're forbidden because of the effect. With the illusion gone, Necromancers would have the ability to cast DD spells during these encounters. With no functional purpose to the illusion, is there an actual reason to keep it?"<P>

<B>This is something that I want to look into further.</B><P>

"2. DOT spells: Very simply, corpses still do poof at times when using these spells. This effects not only epic encounters, but really any encounter that may have a desired drop. 
Solution - With as hard as this has been apparently to recreate on a consistent basis, I don't know what kind of programming solution may be available. If the problem itself cannot be reliably fixed, is there anything that could be established so that (for example) any loot on that monster would remain in play on the ground? That may not be possible, but this needs to be addressed, directly or indirectly."<P>

<B>They shouldn't be poofing any more. Not on NPCs over 55th level, which would include anything considered a raid-level encounter.</B><P>

"3. Mana-dumping: Necromancers make very inefficient manastone's on these raids for the simple reason that they cannot draw mana from the mob. If this is what Necromancer's are left with on epic encounters, it should at least be somewhat efficient. <P>

Solution - if making Lifetaps usable is not an option, could the mana-transfer spells be looked at so they are viable in these situations? Certainly, most would prefer that taps be usable, but if Verant more or less officially sees this as the role of Necromancers on these type of raids, at least make it a viable, efficient one."<P>

<B>Changing the resistance to Lifetap is probably not an option. And making mana transfers more efficient would be a balancing nightmare…<P>

Let me suggest to all of you that there is no reason that your role in this one part of the game can't be different than it is in all other parts of the game. For example, enchanters don't do 'crowd control' on, say Trakonon. Their role there is different than what they do in, say, Guk or wherever. I, personally, don't see a changed role in one part of the post 50 game as a bad thing, not at all. Whether that role is useful enough, now that might be something worth talking about. But a complaint based solely on the fact that your role may be different at one point of the game than it is in others isn't something that I can fully support. I'm not saying that it's not a valid complaint, I just think that it's more of a personal opinion than a threat to the value of the class. And where one personal opinion varies from another… there may be as many necromancers that like being able to support their group on big raids as a change from just beating things up. I don't know, and it's hard for me to know. It's important to keep that in mind during this discussion.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/044525.html">OMG Absor - how poorly you misunderstand the necro 50+ issue</a></B><P>

Your statement that a necro gives hp for mana in relation to the fact clerics give mana for hp is so ludicrous I almost have to laugh!<P>

<B>It would be more useful to explain all that to me in response to the thread that you are responding to. Making a new thread sort of takes everything out of context...<P>

Alan</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
